# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: long-ton
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:long-ton/acre] The **acre** (/ˈeɪkər/ *AY-kər*) is a unit of land area used in the British imperial and the United States customary systems.
[src:long-ton/acre] It is traditionally defined as the area of one chain by one furlong (66 by 660 feet), which is exactly equal to 10 square chains, 1⁄640 of a square mile, 4,840 square yards, or 43,560 square feet, and approximately 4,047 m2, or about 40% of a hectare.
[src:long-ton/acre] The acre is sometimes abbreviated **ac**, but is usually spelled out as the word "acre".
[src:long-ton/acre] Traditionally, in the Middle Ages, an acre was conceived of as the area of land that could be ploughed by one man using a team of eight oxen in one day.
[src:long-ton/acre] The acre is still a statutory measure in the United States, where both the international acre and the US survey acre are in use, but they differ by only four parts per million.
[src:long-ton/acre] The most common use of the acre is to measure tracts of land.
[src:long-ton/acre] The acre is used in many existing and former Commonwealth of Nations countries by custom.
[src:long-ton/acre] In a few, it continues as a statute measure, although not since 2010 in the UK, and not for decades in Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa.
[src:long-ton/acre] In many places where the acre is no longer a statute measure, it is still lawful to use as supplementary information next to the statutory hectare measurement.
[src:long-ton/acre] While all modern variants of the acre contain 4,840 square yards, there are alternative definitions of a yard, so the exact size of an acre depends upon the particular yard on which it is based.
[src:long-ton/acre] Originally, an acre was understood as a strip of land sized at forty perches (660 ft, or 1 furlong) long and four perches (66 ft) wide; this may have also been understood as an approximation of the amount of land a yoke of oxen could plough in one day (a furlong being "a furrow long").
[src:long-ton/acre] A square enclosing one acre is approximately 69.57 yards, or 208 feet 9 inches (63.61 metres), on a side.
[src:long-ton/acre] As a unit of measure, an acre has no prescribed shape; any area of 43,560 square feet is an acre.
[src:long-ton/acre] In the international yard and pound agreement of 1959, the United States and five countries of the Commonwealth of Nations defined the international yard to be exactly 0.9144 metre.
[src:long-ton/acre] The US authorities decided that, while the refined definition would apply nationally in all other respects, the US survey foot (and thus the survey acre) would continue 'until such a time as it becomes desirable and expedient to readjust [it]'.
[src:long-ton/acre] By inference, an "international acre" may be calculated as exactly 4,046.8564224 square metres but it does not have a basis in any international agreement.
[src:long-ton/acre] Both the international acre and the US survey acre contain 1⁄640 of a square mile or 4,840 square yards, but alternative definitions of a yard are used (see *Foot (unit) § Survey foot* and *Yard § Conversions*), so the exact size of an acre depends upon the yard upon which it is based.
[src:long-ton/acre] The US survey acre is about 4,046.872 square metres; its exact value (⁠4046+13,525,426/15,499,969⁠ m2) is based on an inch defined by 1 metre = 39.37 inches exactly, as established by the Mendenhall Order of 1893.
[src:long-ton/acre] Surveyors in the United States use both international and survey feet, and consequently, both varieties of acre.
[src:long-ton/acre] Since the difference between the US survey acre and international acre (0.016 square metres, 160 square centimetres or 24.8 square inches), is only about a quarter of the size of an A4 sheet or US letter, it is usually not important which one is being discussed.
[src:long-ton/acre] Areas are seldom measured with sufficient accuracy for the different definitions to be detectable.
[src:long-ton/acre] In October 2019, the US National Geodetic Survey and the National Institute of Standards and Technology announced their joint intent to end the "temporary" continuance of the US survey foot, mile, and acre units (as permitted by their 1959 decision, above), with effect from the end of 2022.
[src:long-ton/acre] The Puerto Rican *cuerda* (0.39 ha; 0.97 acres) is sometimes called the "Spanish acre" in the continental United States.
[src:long-ton/acre] The acre is commonly used in many current and former Commonwealth countries by custom, and in a few it continues as a statute measure.
[src:long-ton/acre] These include Antigua and Barbuda, American Samoa, The Bahamas, Belize, the British Virgin Islands, Canada, the Cayman Islands, Dominica, the Falkland Islands, Grenada, Ghana, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Jamaica, Montserrat, Samoa, Saint Lucia, St.
[src:long-ton/acre] Vincent and the Grenadines, Turks and Caicos, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:long-ton/acre] In the Republic of Ireland, the hectare is legally used under European units of measurement directives; however, the acre (the same standard statute as used in the UK, not the old Irish acre, which was of a different size) is still widely used, especially in agriculture.
[src:long-ton/acre] In India, residential plots are measured in square feet, square yard or square metre, while agricultural land is measured in bigha, acres or hectare.
[src:long-ton/acre] In Sri Lanka, the division of an acre into 160 perches or 4 roods is common.
[src:long-ton/acre] In Pakistan, residential plots are measured in Kanal (20 *marla* = 1 *kanal* = 605 sq yards) and open/agriculture land measurement is in acres (8 *kanal* = 1 acre) and *muraba* (25 acres = 1 *muraba* = 200 *kanal*), *jerib, wiswa* and *gunta*.
[src:long-ton/acre] Its use as a primary unit for trade in the United Kingdom ceased to be permitted from 1 October 1995, due to the 1994 amendment of the Weights and Measures Act, where it was replaced by the hectare – though its use as a supplementary unit continues to be permitted indefinitely.
[src:long-ton/acre] This was with the exemption of land registration, which records the sale and possession of land; in 2010 HM Land Registry ended its exemption.
[src:long-ton/acre] The measure is still used to communicate with the public, and informally (non-contract) by the farming and property industries.
[src:long-ton/acre] Perhaps the easiest way for US residents to envision an acre is as a rectangle measuring 88 yards by 55 yards (1⁄10 of 880 yards by 1⁄16 of 880 yards), about 9⁄10 the size of a standard American football field.
[src:long-ton/acre] To be more exact, one acre is 90.75% of a 100-yd-long by 53.33-yd-wide American football field (without the end zone).
[src:long-ton/acre] The full field, including the end zones, covers about 1.32 acres (0.53 ha).
[src:long-ton/acre] For residents of other countries, the acre might be envisioned as rather more than half of a 1.76 acres (0.71 ha) football pitch.
[src:long-ton/acre] The word *acre* is derived from the Norman, attested for the first time in 1006 in a text from Fécamp with the meaning of "agrarian measure".
[src:long-ton/acre] In English, an obsolete variant spelling was *aker*.
[src:long-ton/acre] According to the Act on the Composition of Yards and Perches, dating from around 1300, an acre is "40 perches [rods] in length and four in breadth", meaning 220 yards by 22 yards.
[src:long-ton/acre] As detailed in the diagram, an acre was roughly the amount of land tillable by a yoke of oxen in one day.
[src:long-ton/acre] Before the introduction of the metric system, many countries in Europe used their own official "acres" (with other names).
[src:long-ton/acre] In France, the traditional unit of area was the *arpent carré*, a measure based on the Roman system of land measurement.
[src:long-ton/acre] The *acre* was used only in Normandy (and neighbouring places outside its traditional borders), but its value varied greatly across Normandy, ranging from 3,632 to 9,725 square metres, with 8,172 square metres being the most frequent value.
[src:long-ton/acre] But inside the same *pays* of Normandy, for instance in pays de Caux, the farmers (still in the 20th century) made the difference between the *grande acre* (68 ares, 66 centiares) and the *petite acre* (56 to 65 ca).
[src:long-ton/acre] The Normandy *acre* was usually divided in 4 *vergées* (roods) and 160 square *perches*, like the English acre.
[src:long-ton/acre] The Normandy *acre* was equal to 1.6 *arpents*, the unit of area more commonly used in Northern France outside of Normandy.
[src:long-ton/acre] In Germany, the Netherlands, and Eastern Europe the traditional unit of area was *Morgen*.
[src:long-ton/acre] Like the acre, the *morgen* was a unit of ploughland, representing a strip that could be ploughed by one man and an ox or horse in a morning.
[src:long-ton/acre] There were many variants of the *morgen*, differing between the different German territories, ranging from 1⁄2 to 2+1⁄2 acres (2,000 to 10,100 m2).
[src:long-ton/acre] It was also used in Old Prussia, in the Balkans, Norway, and Denmark, where it was equal to about two-thirds acre (2,700 m2).
[src:long-ton/acre] Historically, the size of farms and landed estates in the United Kingdom was usually expressed in acres (or acres, roods, and perches), even if the number of acres was so large that it might conveniently have been expressed in square miles.
[src:long-ton/acre] For example, a certain landowner might have been said to own 32,000 acres of land, not 50 square miles of land.
[src:long-ton/acre] The acre is related to the square mile, with 640 acres making up one square mile.
[src:long-ton/acre] In western Canada and the western United States, divisions of land area were typically based on the square mile, and fractions thereof.
[src:long-ton/acre] If the square mile is divided into quarters, each quarter has a side length of 1⁄2 mile (880 yards) and is 1⁄4 square mile in area, or 160 acres.
[src:long-ton/acre] These subunits are typically then again divided into quarters, with each side being 1⁄4 mile long, and being 1⁄16 of a square mile in area, or 40 acres.
[src:long-ton/acre] In the United States, farmland was typically divided as such, and the phrase "the back 40" refers to the 40-acre parcel to the back of the farm.
[src:long-ton/acre] Most of the Canadian Prairie Provinces and the US Midwest are on square-mile grids for surveying purposes.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In 1959, by international agreement among countries that used the pound as a unit of mass, the *International Avoirdupois Pound* was fixed at the modern definition of exactly 0.45359237 kilograms..
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] It remains the everyday system of weights used in the United States, and is still used, in varying degrees, in everyday life in the United Kingdom, Canada and some other former British colonies, despite their official adoption of the metric system.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The avoirdupois weight system's general attributes were originally developed for the international wool trade in the Late Middle Ages, when trade was in recovery.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] It was historically based on a physical standardized pound or "prototype weight" that could be divided into 16 ounces.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] There were a number of competing measures of mass, and the fact that the avoirdupois pound had three even numbers as divisors (half and half and half again) may have been a cause of much of its popularity, so that the system won out over systems with 12 or 10 or 15 subdivisions.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The use of this unofficial system gradually stabilized and evolved, with only slight changes in the reference standard or in the prototype's actual mass.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In England, Henry VII authorized its use as a standard, and Queen Elizabeth I acted three times to enforce a common standard, thus establishing what became the Imperial system of weights and measures.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Late in the 19th century various governments acted to redefine their base standards on a scientific basis and establish ratios between local avoirdupois measurements and international SI metric system standards.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The legal actions of these various governments were independently conceived, and so did not always pick the same ratios to metric units for each avoirdupois unit.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The result of this was, after these standardisations, measurements of the same name often had marginally different recognised values in different regions (although the pound generally remained very similar).
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Since 1959, there is no difference in the US customary pound and the British imperial pound.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] An alternative system of mass, the troy system, also denominated in pounds and ounces, is generally used for precious materials.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Latin; *peis* = "weight", from Latin *pēnsum*.) This term originally referred to a class of merchandise: *aveir de peis*, "goods of weight", things that were sold in bulk and were weighed on large steelyards or balances.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Only later did the term become identified with a particular *system of units* used to weigh such merchandise.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Inconsistent orthography throughout history has left many variants of the term, such as *haberty-poie* and *haber de peyse*.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] (The Norman *peis* became the Parisian *pois*.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The current spelling of the last word is *poids* in the current standard French orthography, but the spelling *avoirdupois* remained as is in the anglosphere.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] There are two major hypotheses regarding the origins of the avoirdupois system.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The older hypothesis is that it originated in France.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] A newer hypothesis is that it is based on the weight system of Florence.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The avoirdupois weight system is thought to have come into use in England around 1300.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] It was originally used for weighing wool.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In the early 14th century several other specialized weight systems were used, including the weight system of the Hanseatic League with a 16-ounce pound of 7200 grains and an 8-ounce mark.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] However, the main weight system, used for coinage and for everyday use, was based on the 12-ounce tower pound of 5400 grains.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] From the 14th century until the late 16th century, the system's basis and the prototype for today's international pound, the avoirdupois pound, was also known as the **wool pound** or the **avoirdupois wool pound**.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The earliest known version of the avoirdupois weight system had the following units: a pound of 6992 grains, a stone of 14 pounds, a woolsack of 26 stone, an ounce of 1⁄16 pound, and finally, the ounce was divided into 16 "parts".
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The earliest known occurrence of the word "avoirdupois" (or some variant thereof) in England is from a document entitled *Tractatus de Ponderibus et Mensuris* ("Treatise on Weights and Measures").
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] This document is listed in early statute books under the heading *31 Edward I* dated 2 February 1303.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] More recent statute books list it among statutes of uncertain date.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Scholars nowadays believe that it was probably written between 1266 and 1303.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Initially a royal memorandum, it eventually took on the force of law and was recognized as a statute by King Henry VIII and Queen Elizabeth I.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In the *Tractatus*, the word "avoirdupois" refers not to a weight system, but to a class of goods, specifically heavy goods sold by weight, as opposed to goods sold by volume, count, or some other method.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Since it is written in Anglo-Norman French, this document is not the first occurrence of the word in the English language.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The *Tractatus* and other "ancient units" were repealed by the Weights and Measures Act 1824 (5 Geo.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The division and mass of the Avoirdupois units were not significantly changed, but they became tied to actual physical objects and (as a backup) definitions based on physical constants.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] These definitions proved insufficient for recreating the physical prototypes after the 1834 Houses of Parliament fire, and a new Weights and Measures Act 1855 was passed which permitted the recreation of the prototypes from recognized secondary standards.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The Act of 1855 also made the avoirdupois pound the primary unit of mass.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Three major developments occurred during the reign of Edward III (r.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] First, a statute cited as 14 Edw 3 Stat.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The second major development is the statute 25 Edw 3 Stat.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The third development is a set of 14th-century bronze weights at the Westgate Museum in Winchester, England.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The weights are in denominations of 7 pounds (corresponding to a unit known as the clip or wool-clip), 14 pounds (stone), 56 pounds (4 stone) and 91 pounds (1⁄4 sack or woolsack).
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The 91-pound weight is thought to have been commissioned by Edward III in conjunction with the statute of 1350, while the other weights are thought to have been commissioned in conjunction with the statutes of 1340.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The 56-pound weight was used as a reference standard as late as 1588.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In 1588 Queen Elizabeth increased the weight of the avoirdupois pound to 7000 grains and added the troy grain to the avoirdupois weight system.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Prior to 1588, the "part" (1⁄16 ounce) was the smallest unit in the avoirdupois weight system.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In the 18th century, the "part" was renamed "drachm".
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In the United Kingdom, 14 avoirdupois pounds equal one stone.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The quarter, hundredweight, and ton equal respectively, 28 lb, 112 lb, and 2,240 lb in order for masses to be easily converted between them and stone.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The thirteen British colonies in North America used the avoirdupois system, but continued to use the British system as it was, without the evolution that was occurring in Britain in the use of the stone unit.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In 1824 there was landmark new weights and measures legislation in the United Kingdom (Weights and Measures Act 1824) that the United States did not adopt.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The International yard and pound agreement brought the systems closer; for residual differences, see Comparison of the imperial and US customary measurement systems § Weight and mass.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] In the United States, quarters, hundredweights, and tons remain defined as 25, 100, and 2000 lb respectively.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] The quarter is now virtually unused, as is the hundredweight outside of agriculture and commodities.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] If disambiguation is required, then they are referred to as the smaller "short" units in the United States, as opposed to the larger British "long" units.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Grains are used worldwide for measuring gunpowder and smokeless powder charges.
[src:long-ton/avoirdupois-system] Historically, the dram (27+11⁄32 grains, not to be mixed up with the apothecaries' dram of 60 grains) has also been used worldwide for measuring gunpowder charges, particularly for shotguns and large black-powder rifles.
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] The **barleycorn** is an English unit of length equal to 1⁄3 of an inch (i.e. about 8.47 mm).
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] It is still used as the basis of shoe sizes in some English-speaking countries.
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] The notion of three barleycorns composing an inch certainly predates this statute, however, appearing in the 10th-century Welsh Laws of Hywel Dda.
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] In practice, various weights and measures acts of the English kings were standardized with reference to some particular yard-length iron, brass, or bronze bar held by the king or the Royal Exchequer.
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] The formal barleycorn was 1⁄108 of its length.
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] As modern studies show, the actual length of a kernel of barley varies from as short as 0.16–0.28 in (4–7 mm) to as long as 0.47–0.59 in (12–15 mm) depending on the cultivar.
[src:long-ton/barleycorn-unit] Older sources claimed the average length of a grain of barley was 0.345 in (8.8 mm), while that of a grain of "bigg" was 0.3245 in (8.24 mm).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] A **barrel** is one of several units of volume applied in various contexts: there are dry barrels; fluid barrels, such as the British beer barrel and American beer barrel; oil barrels, etc.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] For historical reasons, the volumes of some barrel units are roughly double the volumes of others; volumes in common use range approximately from 100 to 200 litres (22 to 44 imp gal; 26 to 53 US gal).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In many connections, the term **drum** is used almost interchangeably with *barrel*.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Since medieval times, the term *barrel* as a unit of measure has had various meanings throughout Europe, ranging from about 100 litres to about 1,000 litres.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The name was derived in medieval times from the French *baril*, of unknown origin, but still in use, both in French and as derivations in many other languages, such as Italian, Polish, and Spanish.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In most countries, such usage is obsolescent, having been superseded by SI units.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] As a result, the meaning of corresponding words and related concepts (vat, cask, keg etc.) in other languages often refers to a physical container rather than a known measure.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the international oil market context, however, prices in United States dollars per barrel are commonly used, and the term is variously translated, often to derivations of the Latin / Germanic root *fat* (for example *vat* or *Fass*).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In other commercial connections, barrel sizes, such as beer keg volumes, are standardised in many countries.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Fluid barrels vary depending on what is being measured and where.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the UK a beer barrel is 36 imperial gallons (43 US gal; 164 L).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the US most fluid barrels (apart from oil) are 31.5 US gallons (26 imp gal; 119 L) (half a hogshead), but a beer barrel is 31 US gallons (26 imp gal; 117 L).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The size of beer kegs in the US is based loosely on fractions of the US beer barrel.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] When referring to beer barrels or kegs in many countries, the term may be used for the commercial package units independent of actual volume, where common range for professional use is 20–60 L, typically a DIN or *Euro keg* of 50 L.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Richard III, King of England from 1483 until 1485, had defined the wine puncheon as a cask holding 84 wine gallons and a wine tierce as holding 42 wine gallons.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Custom had made the 42 gallon watertight tierce a standard container for shipping eel, salmon, herring, molasses, wine, whale oil, and many other commodities in the English colonies by 1700.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] After the American Revolution in 1776, American merchants continued to use the same size barrels.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] " used in industry typically contain 55 U.S. gallons or 200 litres internationally.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the oil industry, one **barrel** (unit symbol **bbl**) is a unit of volume used for measuring oil defined as exactly 42 US gallons, approximately 159 liters, or 35 imperial gallons.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] According to the American Petroleum Institute (API), a **standard barrel of oil** is the amount of oil that would occupy a volume of exactly 1 barrel (158.99 L) at reference temperature and pressure conditions of 60 °F (15.6 °C) and 14.696 psi (101,325 Pa; 1 atm).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] This standard barrel of oil will occupy a different volume at different pressures and temperatures.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] A standard barrel in this context is thus not simply a measure of volume, but of volume under specific conditions.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Oil companies that are publicly listed in the United States typically report their production using the unit multiples **Mbbl** (one thousand barrels) and **MMbbl** (one million barrels), derived from the Latin word "mille" and Roman Numeral M, meaning "thousand".
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Due to the risk of confusion The Society of Petroleum Engineers recommends in their style guide that abbreviations or prefixes M or MM not be used for barrels of oil or barrel of oil equivalent, but rather that thousands, millions or billions be spelled out.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Using M for thousand and MM for million are in conflict with the SI convention where the "M" prefix stands for "mega" representing million, from the Greek for "large".
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Some oil companies, particularly those based in Europe, use **kb** (kilobarrels, one thousand barrels), **mb** (megabarrels, one million barrels), and **gb** (gigabarrels, one billion barrels).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The lower case m is used to avoid confusion with the capital M used for thousand.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] For the same reason, the unit **kbbl** (one thousand barrels) is also sometimes used.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The first "b" in "bbl" may have been doubled originally to indicate the plural (1 bl, 2 bbl), or possibly it was doubled to eliminate any confusion with bl as a symbol for the bale.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Some sources assert that "bbl" originated as a symbol for "blue barrels" delivered by Standard Oil in its early days.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] However, while Ida Tarbell's 1904 Standard Oil Company history acknowledged the "holy blue barrel", the abbreviation "bbl" had been in use well before the 1859 birth of the U.S. petroleum industry.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Oil wells recover not just oil from the ground, but also natural gas and water.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The term **barrels of liquid per day** (BLPD) refers to the total volume of liquid that is recovered.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Similarly, barrels of oil equivalent or BOE is a value that accounts for both oil and natural gas while ignoring any water that is recovered.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Other terms are used when discussing only oil.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] These terms can refer to either the production of crude oil at an oil well, the conversion of crude oil to other products at an oil refinery, or the overall consumption of oil by a region or country.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] One common term is **barrels per day** (BPD, BOPD, bbl/d, bpd, bd, or b/d), where 1 BPD is equivalent to 0.0292 gallons per minute.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] One BPD also becomes 49.8 tonnes per year.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] At an oil refinery, production is sometimes reported as **barrels per calendar day** (b/cd or bcd), which is total production in a year divided by the days in that year.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Likewise, **barrels per stream day** (BSD or BPSD) is the quantity of oil product produced by a single refining unit during continuous operation for 24 hours.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The task of converting a standard barrel of oil to a standard cubic metre of oil is complicated by the fact that the latter is defined by the API to mean the amount of oil that, at different reference conditions (101.325 kPa and 15 °C (59.0 °F)), occupies 1 cubic metre.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The fact that the reference conditions are not exactly the same means that an exact conversion is impossible unless the exact expansion coefficient of the crude is known, and this will vary from one crude oil to another.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] For a light oil with density of 850 kilogram per cubic metre (API gravity of 35), warming the oil from 59 °F (15 °C) to 60 °F (16 °C) might increase its volume by about 0.047%.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Conversely, a heavy oil with a density of 934 kg/m3 (API gravity of 20) might only increase in volume by 0.039%.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] If physically measuring the density at a new temperature is not possible, then tables of empirical data can be used to accurately predict the change in density.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In turn, this allows maximum accuracy when converting between standard barrel and standard cubic metre.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The logic above also implies the same level of accuracy in measurements for barrels if there is a 1 °F (0.56 °C) error in measuring the temperature at time of measuring the volume.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] For ease of trading, communication and financial accounting, international commodity exchanges often set a conversion factor for benchmark crude oils.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] For instance the conversion factor set by the New York Mercantile Exchange (NYMEX) for Western Canadian Select (WCS) crude oil traded at Hardisty, Alberta, Canada is 6.29287 U.S. barrels per standard cubic metre, despite the uncertainty in converting the volume for crude oil.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Regulatory authorities in producing countries set standards for measurement accuracy of produced hydrocarbons, where such measurements affect taxes or royalties to the government.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the United Kingdom, for instance, the measurement accuracy required is ±0.25%.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] A barrel can technically be used to specify any volume.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Since the actual nature of the fluids being measured varies along the stream, sometimes qualifiers are used to clarify what is being specified.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the oil field, it is often important to differentiate between rates of production of fluids, which may be a mix of oil and water, and rates of production of the oil itself.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] If a well is producing 10 MBD (thousands of barrels per day) of fluids with a 20% water cut, then the well would also be said to be producing 8,000 barrels of oil a day (bod).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In other circumstances, it can be important to include gas in production and consumption figures.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Normally, gas amount is measured in standard cubic feet or standard cubic metres (for volume at STP), as well as in kg or Btu (which do not depend on pressure or temperature).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] But when necessary, such volume is converted to a volume of oil of equivalent enthalpy of combustion.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Production and consumption using this analogue is stated in barrels of oil equivalent per day (boed).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the case of water-injection wells, in the United States it is common to refer to the injectivity rate in barrels of water per day (bwd).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In Canada, it is measured in cubic metres per day (m3/d).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In general, water injection rates will be stated in the same units as oil production rates, since the usual objective is to replace the volume of oil produced with a similar volume of water to maintain reservoir pressure.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Outside the United States, volumes of oil are usually reported in cubic metres (m3) instead of oil barrels.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Cubic metre is the basic volume unit in the International System.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In Canada, oil companies measure oil in cubic metres, but convert to barrels on export, since most of Canada's oil production is exported to the US.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The nominal conversion factor is 1 cubic metre = 6.2898 oil barrels, but conversion is generally done by custody transfer meters on the border, since the volumes are specified at different temperatures, and the exact conversion factor depends on both density and temperature.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Canadian companies operate internally and report to Canadian governments in cubic metres, but often convert to US barrels for the benefit of American investors and oil marketers.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] They generally quote prices in Canadian dollars per cubic metre to other Canadian companies, but use US dollars per barrel in financial reports and press statements, making it appear to the outside world that they operate in barrels.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Companies on the European stock exchanges report the *mass* of oil in tonnes.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Since different varieties of petroleum have different densities, however, there is not a single conversion between mass and volume.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] For example, one tonne of heavy distillates might occupy a volume of 6.1 barrels (970 litres; 256 US gallons).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In contrast, one tonne of crude oil might occupy 6.5 barrels (1,030 litres; 273 US gallons), and one tonne of gasoline will require 7.9 barrels (1,260 litres; 332 US gallons).
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Overall, the conversion is usually between 6 and 8 barrels (954 and 1,270 litres; 252 and 336 US gallons) per tonne.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The measurement of an "oil barrel" originated in the early Pennsylvania oil fields.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The Drake Well, the first oil well in the US, was drilled in Pennsylvania in 1859, and an oil boom followed in the 1860s.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] When oil production began, there was no standard container for oil, so oil and petroleum products were stored and transported in barrels of different shapes and sizes.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Some of these barrels would originally have been used for other products, such as beer, fish, molasses, or turpentine.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Both the 42-US-gallon (159 L) barrels (based on the old English wine measure), the tierce (159 litres) and the 40-US-gallon (150 L) whiskey barrels were used.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Also, 45-US-gallon (170 L) barrels were in common use.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The 40 gallon whiskey barrel was the most common size used by early oil producers, since they were readily available at the time.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Around 1866, early oil producers in Pennsylvania concluded that shipping oil in a variety of different containers was causing buyer distrust.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] They decided they needed a standard unit of measure to convince buyers that they were getting a fair volume for their money, and settled on the standard wine tierce, which was two gallons larger than the standard whisky barrel.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] And by that means, King Richard III's English wine tierce became the American standard oil barrel.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] By 1872, the standard oil barrel was firmly established as 42 US-gallons.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] The 42 gallon standard oil barrel was officially adopted by the Petroleum Producers Association in 1872 and by the U.S.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In modern times, many different types of oil, chemicals, and other products are transported in steel drums.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the United States, these commonly have a capacity of 55 US gallons (208 L) and are referred to as such.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] They are called 200 litre or 200 kg drums outside the United States.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the United Kingdom and its former dependencies, a 44-imperial-gallon (200 L) drum was used, even though all those countries now officially use the metric system and the drums are filled to 200 litres.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] In the United States, the 42 US-gallon size as a unit of measure is largely confined to the oil industry, while different sizes of barrel are used in other industries.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Nearly all other countries use the metric system.
[src:long-ton/barrel-unit] Thus, the 42 US-gallon oil barrel is a unit of measure rather than a physical container used to transport crude oil.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] A **battleship** is a large, heavily armored warship with a main battery consisting of large guns, designed to serve as a capital ship.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] From their advent in the late 1880s, battleships were among the largest and most formidable warship types ever built, until they were surpassed by aircraft carriers beginning in the 1940s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The modern battleship traces its origin to the sailing ship of the line, which was developed into the steam ship of the line and soon thereafter the ironclad warship.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] After a period of extensive experimentation in the 1870s and 1880s, ironclad design was largely standardized by the British *Royal Sovereign* class, which are usually referred to as the first "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] These ships carried an armament that usually included four large guns and several medium-caliber guns that were to be used against enemy battleships, and numerous small guns for self-defense.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Naval powers around the world built dozens of pre-dreadnoughts in the 1890s and early 1900s, though they saw relatively little combat; only two major wars were fought during the period that included pre-dreadnought battles: the Spanish–American War in 1898 and the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The following year, the British launched the revolutionary all-big-gun battleship HMS *Dreadnought*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This ship discarded the medium-caliber guns in exchange for a uniform armament of ten large guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] All other major navies quickly began (or had already started) "dreadnoughts" of their own, leading to a major naval arms race.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] During World War I, only one major fleet engagement took place: the Battle of Jutland in 1916, but neither side was able to achieve a decisive result.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the Interwar period, the major naval powers concluded a series of agreements beginning with the Washington Naval Treaty that imposed limits on battleship building to stop a renewed arms race.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] During this period, relatively few battleships were built, but advances in technology led to the maturation of the fast battleship concept, and several of these ships were built in the 1930s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The treaty system eventually broke down after Japan refused to sign the Second London Naval Treaty in 1936.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Although the rise of the aircraft carrier during World War II largely relegated battleships to secondary duties, they still saw significant action during that conflict.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Notable engagements include the battles of Cape Spartivento and Cape Matapan in 1940 and 1941, respectively; the sortie by the German battleship *Bismarck* in 1941; the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in 1942; and the Battle of Leyte Gulf in 1944.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] After World War II, most battleships were placed in reserve, broken up, or used as target ships, and few saw significant active service during the Cold War.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The four American *Iowa*-class battleships were reactivated during the Korean War in the early 1950s and again in the 1980s as part of the 600-ship Navy.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Even at the height of their dominance of naval combat, some strategists questioned the usefulness of battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Beginning in the mid-1880s, the *Jeune École* (Young School) argued that construction of expensive capital ships should stop in favor of cheap cruisers and torpedo boats.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Despite a period of popularity for the *Jeune École*, the idea fell out of favor and the battleship remained the arbiter of naval combat until World War II.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Even afterward, they remained potent symbols of a country's might and they retained significant psychological and diplomatic effects.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] A number of battleships—predominantly American—remain as museum ships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] A ship of the line was a large, unarmored wooden sailing ship which mounted a battery of up to 120 smoothbore guns and carronades, which came to prominence with the adoption of line of battle tactics in the early 17th century.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] From 1794, the alternative term 'line of battle ship' was contracted to 'battle ship' or 'battleship'.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The sheer number of guns fired broadside meant a ship of the line could wreck any wooden enemy, holing her hull, knocking down masts, wrecking her rigging, and killing her crew.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] They also imparted a psychological effect on the crews of smaller vessels.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Ships of the line were also fairly resilient to the guns of the day; for example, the British Royal Navy lost no first-rate (the largest type of ship of the line) to enemy action during the entire 18th century.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Over time, ships of the line gradually became larger and carried more guns, but otherwise remained quite similar.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Development of the first-rates was particularly conservative, as these ships represented a major investment.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By the early 1800s, the traditional "seventy-four" (so-named because it carried 74 guns) was no longer considered to be a proper ship of the line, having been supplanted by 84- and 120-gun ships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The first major change to the ship of the line concept was the introduction of steam power as an auxiliary propulsion system.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Steam power was gradually introduced to the navy in the first half of the 19th century, initially for small craft and later for frigates.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Early vessels used paddle wheels for propulsion, but by the 1840s, the first screw propeller equipped vessels began to appear.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The value of these smaller steam-powered warships demonstrated their worth, when vessels like the British *Nemesis* proved to be critical to the Anglo-French success in the First Opium War in the 1840s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The French Navy introduced steam to the line of battle with the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850—the first true steam battleship.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] *Napoléon*, which was designed by Henri Dupuy de Lôme, was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This was a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The introduction of steam accelerated the growth in size of battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] France and the United Kingdom were the only countries to develop fleets of wooden, steam-screw battleships although several other navies operated small numbers of screw battleships, including Russia (9), the Ottoman Empire (3), Sweden (2), Naples (1), Denmark (1) and Austria (1).
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Concurrent with the development of steam power, another major technological step heralded the end of the traditional ship of the line: guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Pioneering work was done by the French artillery officer Henri-Joseph Paixhans beginning in 1809.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The American artillerist George Bomford followed not far behind, designing the first shell-firing Columbiad in 1812.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The British and Russians began to follow suit in the 1830s, though early smoothbore guns could not fire shells as far as solid shot, which hampered widespread adoption in any fleet.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By the early 1840s, the French Paixhans gun and American Dahlgren gun had begun to be adopted by their respective navies.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the Crimean War of 1853–1855, six Russian ships of the line and two frigates of the Black Sea Fleet destroyed seven Turkish frigates and three corvettes with explosive shells at the Battle of Sinop in 1853.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The battle was widely seen as vindication of the shell gun.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Despite losing her bowsprit and her foremast, and being set on fire, she was ready for action again the very next day.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] As amply demonstrated at the Battle of Sinop, and again during the Anglo-French blockade of Sevastopol from 1854 to 1855, wooden ships had become vulnerable to shell-firing guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This prompted the French emperor Napoleon III to order the first ironclad warships: the *Dévastation*-class ironclad floating batterys.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Three of these ships led the Anglo-French attack on the Russian fortress on the Kinburn Peninsula in the Battle of Kinburn in 1855, where they bore the brunt of Russian artillery fire, but were not seriously damaged.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The success of these ships prompted the French and British to order several similar vessels.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In March 1858, the French took development of the ironclad to its next logical step: a proper, ocean-going armored warship.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This vessel, another design by Dupuy de Lome, was *Gloire*, and after her launching in 1859, Napoleon III ordered another five similar ships, which sparked a naval arms race with Britain.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The first French ironclads had the profile of a ship of the line, cut to one deck due to weight considerations.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Although made of wood and reliant on sail for most journeys, *Gloire* and her contemporaries were fitted with screw propellers, and their wooden hulls were protected by a layer of thick iron armor.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Britain responded promptly with *Warrior*, a similar but much larger ironclad with an iron hull.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By the time *Warrior* was completed in 1861, another nine ironclads were under construction in British shipyards, some of which were conversions of screw ships of the line that were already being built.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Spain and Russia ordered ironclads in 1861, as did the United States and rebel Confederate States of America after the start of the American Civil War.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Construction of these large and expensive warships remained controversial until March 1862, when news of the Battle of Hampton Roads, fought between the Union USS *Monitor* and the Confederate CSS *Virginia*, firmly settled debate in favor of even larger construction programs.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] From the 1860s to 1880s, navies experimented with the positioning of guns, in turrets, central-batteries, or barbettes; ironclads of the period also prominently used the ram as a principal weapon.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] As steam technology developed, masts were gradually removed from battleship designs.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The British Chief Constructor, Edward Reed, produced the *Devastation*-class ironclads in 1869.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] These were mastless turret ships, which adopted twin-screw propulsion and an arrangement of two pairs of 12-inch (305 mm) guns, one fore and one aft of the superstructure, that prefigured the advent of the pre-dreadnought battleship some two decades later.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By the mid-1870s steel was used as a construction material alongside iron and wood.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The French Navy's *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876, was a combination central battery and barbette ship, which became the first capital ship in the world to use steel as the principal building material.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The rapid pace of technological developments, particularly in terms of gun capabilities and thickness of armor to combat them, quickly rendered ships obsolescent.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the continuous attempt by gun manufacturers to keep ahead of developments in armor plate, larger and larger guns were fitted to many of the later ironclads.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Some of these, such as the British *Victoria* class, carried guns as large as 16.25 inches (413 mm) in diameter, while the Italian *Duilio*-class ironclads were armed with colossal 17.7-inch (450 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the 1880s, opposition to fleets of large, expensive ironclads arose around the world, but most notably in France, where a group of naval officers led by Admiral Théophile Aube formed the *Jeune École* (Young School).
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The theory, which held as one of its core tenets that small, cheap torpedo boats could easily defeat ironclads, was based on combat experience during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The doctrine also posited that modern steel-hulled cruisers could defeat a more powerful navy by attacking the country's merchant shipping, rather than engage in a direct battle.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The concept proved to be highly influential for several years, shaping the construction programs of France, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary, among others throughout the world.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In 1889, the British government passed the Naval Defence Act 1889, which embarked on a major naval construction program aimed at establishing the so-called two-power standard, whereby the Royal Navy would be stronger than the next two largest navies combined.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The plan saw the construction of the eight *Royal Sovereign*-class battleships, which have been regarded as the first class of battleship that would retrospectively be referred to as "pre-dreadnought battleships".
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] These large battleships incorporated a number of major improvements over earlier vessels like the *Devastation*s, including a high freeboard for true ocean-going capability, more extensive armor protection, heavier secondary battery guns, and greater speed.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The ships were armed with four 13.5 in (340 mm) guns in two twin mounts, fore and aft, which established the pattern for subsequent battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] After building a trio of smaller second class battleships intended for the colonial empire, Britain followed with the nine-strong *Majestic*-class battleships in 1893–1895, which improved on the basic *Royal Sovereign* design.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] These ships adopted the 12 in (305 mm) gun, which would become the standard for all subsequent British pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Foreign navies quickly began pre-dreadnoughts of their own; France began *Brennus* in 1889 and Germany laid down four *Brandenburg*-class battleships in 1890.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The United States Navy laid down three *Indiana*-class battleships in 1891, the same year work began on the Russian battleship *Tri Sviatitelia*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Japan ordered the two *Fuji*-class battleships from British yards, to an improved *Royal Sovereign* design, in 1894.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Navy eventually ordered its own pre-dreadnoughts, beginning with the *Habsburg* class in 1899.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] All of these ships carried guns of between 11 and 13.4 in (280 and 340 mm), save the Austro-Hungarian vessels, which, being significantly smaller than the rest, only carried 9.4 in (240 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] They also generally carried a light armament for defense against torpedo boats and other light craft.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Some ships varied from this general pattern, such as the American *Indiana*s, which carried a heavier secondary battery of 8-inch (203 mm) guns, and the German *Brandenburg*s, which had six 11-inch guns for instead of the usual four heavy guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Many of the early French pre-dreadnoughts, such as *Charles Martel*, carried a mixed heavy armament of two 12-inch and two 10.8-inch (274 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnoughts continued the technical innovations of the ironclad throughout the 1890s and early 1900s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Compound armor gave way to much stronger Harvey armor developed in the United States in 1890, which was in turn superseded by the German Krupp armor in 1894.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] As armor became stronger, it could be reduced in thickness considerably, which saved weight that could be allocated to other aspects of the ship design, and generally permitted larger and more capable battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] At the same time, the advent of smokeless powder continued the trend begun in the French navy of comparatively smaller guns firing at higher velocities.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Early on in the pre-dreadnought era, most navies standardized on the 12-inch gun; only Germany remained the significant outlier, relying on 11-inch and even 9.4-inch guns for its pre-dreadnoughts.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Similarly, later in the pre-dreadnought era, the secondary batteries grew in caliber, usually to 7 to 8 in (178 to 203 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the last years of the 19th century and the first years of the 20th, the escalation in the building of battleships became an arms race between Britain and Germany.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The German naval laws of 1890 and 1898 authorized a fleet of 38 battleships, a vital threat to the balance of naval power.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Britain answered with further shipbuilding, but by the end of the pre-dreadnought era, British supremacy at sea had markedly weakened.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In 1883, the United Kingdom had 38 ironclad battleships, twice as many as France and almost as many as the rest of the world put together.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In 1897, Britain's lead was far smaller due to competition from France, Germany, and Russia, as well as the development of pre-dreadnought fleets in Italy, the United States and Japan.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Ottoman Empire, Spain, Sweden, Denmark, Norway, the Netherlands, Chile, and Brazil all had second-rate fleets led by armored cruisers, coastal defence ships or monitors.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Pre-dreadnought battleships received their first test in combat in the Spanish–American War in 1898 at the Battle of Santiago de Cuba.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] An American squadron that included four pre-dreadnoughts had blockaded a Spanish squadron of four armored cruisers in Santiago de Cuba until 3 July, when the Spanish ships attempted to break through and escape.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] All four cruisers were destroyed in the ensuing engagement, as were a pair of Spanish destroyers, and the American ships received little damage in return.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The battle seemed to indicate that the mixed batteries of pre-dreadnought battleships were very effective, as the medium-caliber guns had inflicted most of the damage (which reinforced the observations of the Battle of Manila Bay, where only cruisers armed with medium guns had been present).
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] It also led navies around the world to begin working on better solutions for rangefinding in the hope of improving gunnery at longer ranges.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Conflicting colonial ambitions in Korea and Manchuria led Russia and Japan to the next major use of pre-dreadnoughts in combat.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] During the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905, squadrons of battleships engaged in a number of battles, including the Battle of the Yellow Sea and the Battle of Tsushima.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Naval mines also proved to be a deadly threat to battleships on both sides, sinking the Russian *Petropavlovsk* in March 1904 and the Japanese battleships *Hatsuse* and *Yashima* on the same day in May.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The action in the Yellow Sea began during a Russian attempt to break out of Port Arthur, which the Japanese under Admiral Tōgō Heihachirō had blockaded.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Russians outmaneuvered the Japanese and briefly escaped, but the latter's superior speed allowed them to catch up.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] A 12-inch shell struck the Russian flagship, killing the squadron commander and causing the Russian ships to fall into disarray and retreat back to Port Arthur.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] With night falling, the Japanese broke off and reimposed the blockade.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] At Tsushima, Togo outmaneuvered the Russian Second Pacific Squadron that had been sent to reinforce the Pacific Fleet, and the Japanese battleships quickly inflicted fatal damage with long-range fire from their 12-inch guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In both actions during the Russo-Japanese War, the fleets engaged at longer range (as far as 12,000 yd (11,000 m) at the Yellow Sea), where only their 12-inch guns were effective.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Only in the final stages of the battle at Tsushima, by which time the Russian fleet had been severely damaged and most of its modern battleships sunk or disabled, did the Japanese fleet close to effective range of their secondary guns, fighting as close as 2,700 yd (2,500 m).
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The actions, particularly the decisive engagement at Tsushima, demonstrated that the lessons taken from the Spanish–American War were incorrect, and that the large-caliber gun should be the only offensive weapon carried by battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the early 1900s, some naval theorists had begun to argue for future battleships to discard the heavy secondary batteries and instead carry only big guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The first prominent example was Vittorio Cuniberti, the chief engineer of the Italian *Regia Marina* (Royal Navy); he published an article in 1903 titled "An Ideal Battleship for the British Navy" in *Jane's Fighting Ships*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Japanese Navy was the first to actually order any of these new ships, beginning with the two *Satsuma*-class battleships in 1904, though due to shortages of 12-inch guns, they were completed with a mix of 12- and 10-inch (254 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By early 1905, Fisher had converted to the 12-inch gun for his proposed new capital ships, and in March that year, the German Navy had decided to build an all-big-gun battleship for the planned *Nassau* class.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The American *South Carolina* class was authorized in 1905, but work did not begin until December 1906.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Though several navies had begun design work on all-big-gun battleships, the first to be completed was the British *Dreadnought*, which had been ordered by Fisher.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] He actually preferred a very large armored cruiser equipped with an all-big-gun armament, which would come to be known as the battlecruiser, and he only included *Dreadnought* in his 1905 construction program to appease naval officers who favored continued battleship building.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Fisher believed that Britain's security against the French and Russian threats would be better guaranteed by squadrons of fast battlecruisers, three of which were laid down in 1906.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Regardless of Fisher's intentions, the rapidly changing strategic calculus invalidated his plans and ensured that when the 1906–1907 program was being debated, Germany would be Britain's primary rival, the Royal Navy chose to build three more dreadnoughts instead of further battlecruisers.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Reactions from the other naval powers was immediate; very few pre-dreadnoughts were built afterward, and in the first seven years of the ensuing arms race, all of the major naval powers either had their own dreadnoughts in service or nearing completion.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Of these competitions, the Anglo-German race was the most significant, though others took place, such as the South American contest.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Even naval powers of the second and third rank, such as Spain; Brazil, Chile, and Argentina in South America; and Greece and the Ottoman Empire in the Mediterranean had begun dreadnought programs, either domestically or ordering abroad.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Technological development continued over the decade that followed *Dreadnought*'s launch.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Already by 1910, the British had begun the first of the so-called "super-dreadnoughts" that carried significantly more powerful 13.5-inch (340 mm) guns, all on the centerline.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The United States followed suit in 1911, though increasing the caliber of their guns to 14 inches (356 mm).
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] France adopted a 13.4 in (340 mm) gun for its *Bretagne*-class battleships, laid down in 1912.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] That year, Japan laid down the first of its *Fusō*-class battleships, also armed with a 14-inch main battery.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Germans waited until 1913, but skipped directly to 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By this time, Britain had led the way to the 15-inch gun with the *Queen Elizabeth* class begun in late 1912.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] But more importantly than the increase of caliber, the *Queen Elizabeth*s were the first completely oil-fired battleships and the first fast battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] At around the same time, the United States introduced the next major innovation in battleship design: the all or nothing armor system in the *Nevada* class laid down in 1912.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The heaviest possible armor was used to protect the ship's propulsion machinery and ammunition magazines, but intermediate protection was stripped away from non-essential areas, since this mid-weight armor only served to detonate armor-piercing shells.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By the start of World War I in July 1914, the Royal Navy's Grand Fleet outnumbered the German High Seas Fleet by 21 to 13 in numbers of dreadnought battleships and 4 to 3 in battlecruisers.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] And over the course of the war, Britain would add another 14 dreadnoughts, while Germany completed another 6.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] German strategy presumed that Britain would launch an immediate offensive into the southern North Sea, but the British preferred to establish a distant blockade, which very quickly stopped German maritime trade.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Both sides were aware that, because of the greater number of British dreadnoughts, a full fleet engagement would be likely to result in a British victory.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The German strategy was therefore to try to provoke an engagement on their terms: either to induce a part of the Grand Fleet to enter battle alone, or to fight a pitched battle near the German coastline, where friendly minefields, torpedo-boats and submarines could be used to even the odds.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The British fleet commander, Admiral John Jellicoe, refused to be drawn into unfavorable conditions and enforced the blockade at the English Channel and between Scotland and Norway.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the Baltic Sea, Germany found itself in the reverse situation, in an even more lopsided fashion versus its Russian opponent.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Russian Baltic Fleet had only four dreadnoughts at the start of the war, so they adopted a purely defensive approach to guard the capital at Petrograd and the northern flank of the Russian army units fighting on the Eastern Front.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the Mediterranean Sea, Italy initially remained neutral, despite being a member of the Triple Alliance with Germany and Austria-Hungary, leaving the latter to face the French Navy and British Mediterranean Fleet alone.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] After ensuring the French army units in French North Africa were safely convoyed to France, the French fleet sailed to the Adriatic Sea to blockade the Austro-Hungarian fleet, which refused to leave their fortified bases.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The French, like the other major European naval commanders, had failed to consider that their opponents would not concede to engaging in battle on terms unfavorable to them.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Adriatic quickly turned into another stalemate as the threat of Austro-Hungarian mines and submarines prevented a more aggressive employment of the French fleet.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Germans embarked on a number of sweeps into the North Sea and raids on British coastal towns to draw out part of the Grand Fleet, which would be isolated and destroyed.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] These included the raid on Scarborough, Hartlepool and Whitby, where the Germans nearly caught an isolated British battle squadron, but turned away, thinking that it was the entire Grand Fleet.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This strategy ultimately led to the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, the largest clash of battleship fleets.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The first stage of the battle was fought largely by the two sides' battlecruiser squadrons, though the British were supported by four of the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] After both battleship fleets engaged, the British crossed the Germans' "T" twice, but the latter managed to extricate themselves from the action as darkness fell.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Early on 1 June, the High Seas Fleet had reached port.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the course of the fighting, three British battlecruisers were destroyed, as was one German battlecruiser and the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Numerous cruisers and destroyers were lost on both sides as well.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Germans made two further offensive operations in the months after Jutland.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The first, which led to the inconclusive action of 19 August, saw one German battleship torpedoed by a British submarine and two British cruisers sunk by German U-boats.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This incident convinced the British that the risks posed by submarines were too great to send the Grand Fleet into the southern North Sea, barring exceptional circumstances like a German invasion of Britain.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the second German operation, which took place on 18–19 October, a German cruiser was damaged by a submarine and the Grand Fleet remained in port.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By this time, the Germans were similarly convinced of the futility of their attempts to isolate part of the British fleet, and discontinued such raids.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] They instead turned to unrestricted submarine warfare, which resulted in their battleships being reduced to a supporting force that guarded the U-boat bases.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the Baltic, the Germans made two attempts to capture the islands in the Gulf of Riga.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The first came in August 1915, and in the ensuing Battle of the Gulf of Riga, a pair of German dreadnoughts engaged in an artillery duel at long range with the Russian pre-dreadnought *Slava* guarding the minefields that protected the gulf.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Germans drove off the Russian ship, cleared the minefield, but by the time they entered the gulf, submarines had reportedly arrived.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Unwilling to risk the battleships in the shallow, confined waters of the gulf, the Germans retreated.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The second attempt—Operation Albion—took place in October 1917.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] During the Battle of Moon Sound, another pair of German dreadnoughts damaged *Slava* so badly that she had to be scuttled, and the Germans completed their amphibious assault on the islands.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The modern units of the French and British fleets in the Mediterranean spent much of the war guarding the entrance to the Adriatic, first based at Malta and later moving to Corfu.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] They saw very little action through the war.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] For their part, the Italians were content to reinforce the blockading force guarding the Adriatic, as they, too, were unwilling to risk their capital ships in the mine and submarine infested waters of the Austrian Littoral.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Instead, light forces carried out most of the operations.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Meanwhile, several French and British pre-dreadnoughts were sent to attack the Ottoman defenses guarding the Dardanelles.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the ensuing naval operations from February to March 1915, several battleships were sunk or damaged by mines and torpedoes.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] When the fleets failed to break through the defenses, the British and French decided to land at Gallipoli to try to take the fortifications by land; the remaining battleships were thereafter used to provide naval gunfire support.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This, too, ultimately failed and by January 1916, the British and French withdrew their troops.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Russian battleships saw more action in the Black Sea against their Ottoman opponents.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By 1916, the Russians had completed a pair of dreadnoughts in the Black Sea, which severely curtailed Ottoman freedom of maneuver.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the course of the war, older pre-dreadnoughts proved to be highly vulnerable to underwater damage, whether by naval mine or ship-launched or submarine-delivered torpedoes.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] HMS *Formidable* was sunk by a German U-boat in the English Channel in 1915.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] At the Dardanelles, HMS *Majestic* was sunk by a German U-boat, HMS *Goliath* was sunk by the Ottoman destroyer *Muavenet-i Milliye*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The British *Ocean* and *Irresistible* and the French *Bouvet* were all sunk by mines.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] HMS *Russell* and HMS *Cornwallis* were both sunk by mines in the Mediterranean in 1916 and 1917, respectively.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] HMS *King Edward VII* was similarly mined and sunk off the British coast in 1916, and HMS *Britannia* was sunk by a U-boat in the final days of the war.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The French *Gaulois* and *Suffren* were sunk by U-boats in 1916, and *Danton* was torpedoed and sunk by a U-boat in 1917.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] At Jutland, the only battleship lost was the old pre-dreadnought *Pommern*, which was torpedoed by a destroyer.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In contrast, dreadnoughts proved to be much more resilient to underwater attack.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] HMS *Marlborough* was damaged by a torpedo at Jutland, but nevertheless returned to port.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The German SMS *Westfalen* was torpedoed at the action of 19 August 1916, and SMS *Grosser Kurfürst* and *Kronprinz* were torpedoed by the same submarine in November 1917; all three survived.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] SMS *Bayern* was mined during Operation Albion and remained in action against Russian artillery batteries for some time thereafter.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Dreadnoughts lost to underwater attack were rare.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] HMS *Audacious* was sunk by a mine in October 1914, the Austro-Hungarian SMS *Szent Istvan* was sunk by Italian MAS boats in June 1918, and five months later, Italian frogmen sank *Viribus Unitis* using a powerful limpet mine.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the immediate aftermath of the war, the most modern units of the German fleet was interned at Scapa Flow, where in June 1919, their crews scuttled the fleet to avoid it being handed over to the Allies.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The remaining dreadnoughts still in German ports were therefore seized as compensation for the scuttled ships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The postwar *Reichsmarine* of Weimar Germany was limited to a contingent of eight old pre-dreadnoughts (of which two would be kept in reserve) under the terms of the Treaty of Versailles; new battleships were subject to severe restrictions on size and armament.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The surviving battleships of Austria-Hungary, the other defeated Central Power, were soon distributed among the Allies, to be broken up.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] While the other major naval powers remained free to build new battleships, most of them were financially crippled after the war.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The prospect of a renewed naval arms race between the United States, United Kingdom, and Japan, appealed to few politicians in the three countries, and so they concluded the Washington Naval Treaty in 1922, which also included Italy and France.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The treaty limited the number and size of battleships, and imposed a ten-year building holiday, along with other provisions.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The treaty also imposed a ratio of 5:5:3 on total displacement of battleships for the US, UK, and Japan, respectively, and it severed the Anglo-Japanese Alliance.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The only exceptions to the building holiday were for the two British *Nelson*-class battleships, which were permitted to give Britain parity with the latest American and Japanese battleships, which were all armed with 16-inch (406 mm) guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Washington treaty was followed by a series of other naval treaties, including the First London Naval Treaty (1930) and the Second London Naval Treaty (1936), which both set additional limits on major warships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The treaty limitations meant that fewer new battleships were launched in 1919–1939 than in 1905–1914.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The treaties also inhibited development by imposing upper limits on the weights of ships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Designs like the projected British N3-class battleship, the first American *South Dakota* class, and the Japanese *Kii* class—all of which continued the trend to larger ships with bigger guns and thicker armor—never got off the drawing board.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Those designs which were commissioned during this period were referred to as treaty battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The collapse of the treaty system began during the negotiations for the Second London Treaty, where Japan demanded parity with Britain and the US, which the latter two flatly rejected.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Japan withdrew from the treaty system in 1936, though the agreements remained in effect until January 1937.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] As early as 1914, the British Admiral Percy Scott predicted that battleships would soon be made irrelevant by aircraft.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Between 1916 and 1918, US Admiral William Fullam published a series of papers stating that aircraft would become an independent strike arm of the fleet, and argued that the *Lexington*-class battlecruisers then under construction should be converted to aircraft carriers than scrapped.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By the end of World War I, aircraft had successfully adopted the torpedo as a weapon.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In 1921 the Italian general and air theorist Giulio Douhet completed a hugely influential treatise on strategic bombing titled *The Command of the Air*, which foresaw the dominance of air power over conventional military and naval forces.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In 1921, US General Billy Mitchell used the ex-German dreadnought SMS *Ostfriesland* in a series of bombing tests conducted by the Navy and Army.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The test involved a series of attacks on the stationary, unmanned ships using low-level, land-based bombers dropping bombs that ranged from 550 to 2,000 pounds (250 to 910 kg).
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] *Ostfriesland* was sunk by the heaviest bombs, though Mitchell broke the rules of the tests and the subsequent report concluded that had the ship been crewed, underway, and firing back at the aircraft, damage control teams aboard *Ostfriesland* could have managed any damage inflicted.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Mitchell and his supporters nevertheless embarked on a public campaign that falsely claimed that *Ostfriesland* was a super-battleship, and the quick sinking proved that battleships were obsolete.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Mitchell would eventually be subjected to a court martial, convicted, and discharged from the Army over his insubordinate tactics.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Naval aviation traces its origin back to the first decade of the 20th century, though early efforts were based on using aircraft to scout for the fleet and help direct gunfire at long range.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] A number of experimental aircraft carriers were employed during World War I, primarily by the Royal Navy, all converted from merchant vessels or existing warships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The US Navy completed its first carrier, USS *Langley*, in 1922.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] But aircraft carriers in the 1920s faced a number of challenges to be overcome: aircraft of the day were short-ranged, which meant the carrier had to be very close to the enemy to be able to launch and then recover a strike, which exposed the carriers to attack.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In addition, the available planes had insufficient power to carry meaningful bomb loads.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Early naval aviators nevertheless pioneered effective tactics like dive bombing during this period.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Because the Washington Treaty system precluded the construction of any new battleships until the early 1930s, the major naval powers began a program of modernization for their most effective battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Britain conducted a series of refits to their *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships through the 1920s, adding anti-torpedo bulges, additional anti-aircraft guns, and aircraft catapults; further refits in the 1930s increased armor protection and further strengthened their anti-aircraft batteries.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The *Revenge*-class battleships were less heavily modified during the period.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The US *Florida*, *Wyoming* class, and *New York* classes received similar treatments in the 1920s, while the *Nevada* and *Pennsylvania* classes received new turbines, additional armor, and more anti-aircraft guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Japanese similarly updated their *Fusō*, *Ise*, and *Nagato*-class battleships, and rebuilt three of the four *Kongō*-class battlecruisers into fast battleships, albeit with significantly inferior protection compared to the other ships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] They all also received distinctive pagoda masts.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] *Hiei* was initially disarmed to serve as a training ship under the terms of the Washington Treaty, but was remilitarized in the late 1930s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In the 1930s, all four classes were lengthened and had their propulsion systems improved to increase their speeds.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The French and Italian navies were exempted from the 10-year building holiday, owing to the comparative obsolescence of their battleships; they were permitted to build 70,000 long tons (71,000 t) worth of battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] But the weak economies of both countries led both to defer new construction until Germany began building the *Deutschland* class of heavily armed cruiser at the end of the 1920s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This prompted the French to build the *Dunkerque* class of small, fast battleships armed with 13 in (330 mm) guns, which led to a short arms race in Europe in the mid-1930s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Italians responded with the significantly larger and more powerful *Littorio* class, armed with 15-inch guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The French, in turn, began the *Richelieu*-class battleships to counter the *Littorio*s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] By this time, Nazi Germany had signed the Anglo-German Naval Agreement in 1935, which removed the restrictions imposed by Versailles and pegged German naval strength to 35% of British tonnage.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] This permitted the construction of two *Scharnhorst*-class battleships, which were also a response to the *Dunkerque*s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The advent of the *Richelieu*s prompted the Germans to build the two *Bismarck*-class battleships late in the decade.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The Germans thereafter embarked on the ambitious Plan Z naval construction program, which included a total of eight battleships, of which the *Bismarck*s would be the first two.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] Against the backdrop of European rearmament in the mid-1930s, Britain began planning its first battleship class in a decade: the *King George V* class.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] These were armed with 14-inch guns intended to comply with the terms of the Second London Naval Conference, and they were laid down in 1937.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] The United States began their *North Carolina* class at the same time, and though they were intended to be armed with 14-inch guns, Japan's refusal to agree to the Second London Treaty led the US to invoke a clause of the treaty that allowed an increase to 16-inch guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] In 1939, these were followed by the four *South Dakota*-class battleships, and in 1940 by the first of four *Iowa*-class battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p01] For its part, Japan had decided to embark on a program of four very large *Yamato*-class battleships, armed with 18-inch (457 mm) guns, as early as 1934, though work did not begin on the first ship until late 1937.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The German pre-dreadnought *Schleswig-Holstein* fired the first shots of World War II by initiating the bombardment of the Polish garrison at Westerplatte in the early hours on 1 September 1939.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The German *Scharnhorst*-class battleships caught the British carrier HMS *Glorious* off the coast of Norway and sank her during the Norwegian campaign.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] In the former action, the British sank a pair of older *Bretagne*-class battleships and the fast battleship *Dunkerque*, though the latter was refloated and repaired.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] At Dakar, the French battleship *Richelieu* and other forces fended off the British task force, which resulted in the torpedoing of the battleship HMS *Resolution*, which was severely damaged.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Italy entered the war in June 1940, shortly before the French defeat.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] In November, the British launched a nighttime airstrike on the naval base at Taranto; in the Battle of Taranto, Fairey Swordfish torpedo bombers disabled three Italian battleships, though they were subsequently repaired.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Over the next year, Italian and British battleships engaged in a number of inconclusive actions as they contested the supply lines to North Africa.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] These included the Battle of Cape Spartivento in November 1940 and the Battle of Cape Matapan in March 1941.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] At Matapan, the battleship *Vittorio Veneto* was badly damaged by a Swordfish, though the ship returned to port.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The British battleships *Valiant*, *Warspite*, and *Barham* nevertheless caught a group of three heavy cruisers that evening and destroyed them in a furious, close-range night action.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Convoy battles continued through 1941 and into 1942, with actions such as First and Second Sirte.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] By 1943, Italian operations were sharply reduced due to a shortage of fuel, and after the Allied invasion of Italy, the country surrendered, allowing most of its fleet to be interned at Malta.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] While on the way, the battleship *Roma* was sunk by a German Fritz X guided glide bomb.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] In the meantime, in January 1941, the Germans began to send their few battleships on commerce raiding operations in the Atlantic, starting with the two *Scharnhorst*-class ships in Operation Berlin, which was not particularly successful.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Bismarck* followed with Operation Rheinübung in May, which resulted in two actions, the Battle of the Denmark Strait and the sinking of *Bismarck*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] During the operation, *Bismarck* was crippled by Swordfish torpedo bombers, which allowed a pair of British battleships to catch and destroy her.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] By 1942, the last operational German battleships—*Tirpitz* and *Scharnhorst*—were sent to occupied Norway to serve as a fleet in being to tie down British naval resources and to attack supply convoys to the Soviet Union.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The battleship HMS *Duke of York* eventually sank *Scharnhorst* at the Battle of North Cape in December 1943, and *Tirpitz* was destroyed by British heavy bombers in 1944.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] On 7 December 1941, the Japanese launched a surprise attack on the US naval base at Pearl Harbor.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Over the course of two waves of dive-, level- and torpedo bombers, the Japanese sank or destroyed five battleships and inflicted serious damage to the facilities there.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Three days later, land-based Japanese aircraft operating out of French Indochina, then occupied by Japan, caught and sank the British battleship HMS *Prince of Wales* and the battlecruiser HMS *Repulse* off the coast of British Malaya.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Though the Taranto and Pearl Harbor strikes were significant steps toward aircraft replacing the battleship as the primary naval striking arm, the sinking of *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* marked the first time aircraft had sunk capital ships that were maneuvering and returning fire.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Employment of battleships during the Pacific War was limited by a number of factors.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Japanese strategic doctrine, the *Kantai Kessen*, envisioned a decisive clash of battleships at the end of the war, and so kept most of their battleships in home waters, and only the four *Kongō*s were routinely detached to escort the aircraft carriers of the *Kido Butai*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] For their part, the US kept its surviving pre-war battleships out of action primarily because they were too slow to keep up with the carriers.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Later in the war, they were employed as coastal bombardment vessels.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Nevertheless, American and Japanese battleships saw significant action during the Guadalcanal campaign in 1942, most notably at the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal in November.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] There, an American squadron centered on the battleships *Washington* and *South Dakota* intercepted and sank the battleship *Kirishima*, though *South Dakota* received significant damage in return.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] As more and more of the American fast battleships entered service from 1942, onward, they were frequently used as escorts for the fast carrier task force that was the US Navy's primary striking arm in its campaign across the central Pacific.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] During the Philippines campaign, battleships played a central role during the Battle of Leyte Gulf in October 1944.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The action was one of the largest naval battles in history, which took place over several days and as three Japanese fleets attacked the Allied invasion fleet.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The Japanese battleship *Musashi*, part of Center Force, was sunk by American carrier aircraft during the Battle of Sibuyan Sea on 24 October.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Surigao Strait the following night, several US battleships that had been repaired from the attack on Pearl Harbor defeated the Japanese Southern Force that included a pair of battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Center Force attacked again on 25 October in the Battle off Samar, but was driven off by destroyers and aircraft from several escort carriers.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] During the Battle of Okinawa in April 1945, Japan sent *Yamato* as a final suicide mission to attack the landing beaches and attempt to stop the invasion of the island.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] American aircraft scored between nine and thirteen torpedo hits and six bomb hits on the ship and sank her.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Haruna* was sunk by US aircraft off Kure, Japan, in July.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The war ended with the Japanese surrender aboard the battleship USS *Missouri* in September 1945.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] After World War II, several navies retained their existing battleships, but most were either placed in their reserve fleets or scrapped outright.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Of their surviving pre-war battleships, most of the American vessels were either scrapped or sunk as target ships by 1948, though the most modern vessels, those of the *Tennessee* and *Maryland* classes, survived until the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] One of the earlier vessels, USS *Texas*, was preserved as a museum ship.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The four *King George V*-class ships were all broken up by 1957, Only two battleships—the British HMS *Vanguard* and the French *Jean Bart*—were completed after the war.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Vanguard* did not long outlast the *King George V*s, being scrapped herself in 1960.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Jean Bart* (and her sister *Richelieu*) remained in the French fleet's inventory until the early 1960s, when they were discarded.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Three of the six American *North Carolina*- and *South Dakota*-class ships were similarly scrapped in the early 1960s, but the other three—*North Carolina*, *Massachusetts*, and *Alabama*—were retained as museum ships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] With the reduced naval budgets of the immediate postwar period, the US Navy chose to concentrate its resources on its carrier force.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Besides the rise of aircraft carriers as the preeminent naval striking force, the advent of nuclear weapons influenced the decision to abandon large battleship fleets.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] In 1946, *Nagato*, which was seized by the US, and four American battleships were used during the Operation Crossroads nuclear weapons tests, though three of the American ships survived the two blasts and were later sunk with conventional weapons.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Of the remaining, smaller battleships fleets, Italy retained its two *Andrea Doria*-class battleships, of 1913 vintage, until the late 1950s and early 1960s, when they were scrapped.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] One other battleship, *Giulio Cesare* was taken by the Soviets as reparations and renamed *Novorossiysk*; she was sunk by a mine in the Black Sea on 29 October 1955.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The two surviving *Littorio*-class ships were taken by the US and UK as war reparations and scrapped in the late 1940s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The Soviets still had a pair of World War I-era battleships—*Parizhskaya Kommuna* and *Gangut*—but they, too, were scrapped in the late 1950s.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The three large South American navies still had a handful of pre-World War I dreadnoughts in service after the war.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Brazil eventually discarded its two *Minas Gerais*-class battleships in the early 1950s; *Argentina* sold its two *Rivadavia*-class battleships in 1956; the last ship in the region, the Chilean *Almirante Latorre*, followed them to the breakers' yard in 1959.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The four *Iowa*-class battleships were the only vessels of the type to see significant combat after World War II.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] All four ships were reactivated for gunfire support duties during the Korean War in the early 1950s, and *New Jersey* was also deployed during the Vietnam War in 1968–1969 for the same task.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] All four ships were modernized in the early 1980s with Tomahawk cruise missiles, Harpoon anti-ship missiles, and Phalanx CIWS systems, along with the latest radar systems.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] They were recommissioned as part of the 600-ship Navy program under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *New Jersey* next saw action in 1982, bombarding Syrian artillery during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* took part in Operation Desert Storm against Iraqi forces in 1991, bombarding enemy positions along the coast.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The ships proved to be expensive to operate, and they required thousands of men to keep in service, so *Iowa* and *New Jersey* were already back in reserve by that time, and *Missouri* and *Wisconsin* were also decommissioned by the end of 1991.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] All four were struck from the Naval Vessel Register in 1995.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] When the last *Iowa*-class ship was finally stricken from the Naval Vessel Registry, no battleships remained in service or in reserve with any navy worldwide.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] A number are preserved as museum ships, either afloat or in drydock.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The U.S. has eight battleships on display: *Massachusetts*, *North Carolina*, *Alabama*, *Iowa*, *New Jersey*, *Missouri*, *Wisconsin*, and *Texas*.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Missouri* and *New Jersey* are museums at Pearl Harbor and Camden, New Jersey, respectively.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Iowa* is on display as an educational attraction at the Los Angeles Waterfront in San Pedro, California.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Wisconsin* now serves as a museum ship in Norfolk, Virginia.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Massachusetts*, which has the distinction of never having lost a man during service, is on display at the Battleship Cove naval museum in Fall River, Massachusetts.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Texas*, the first battleship turned into a museum, is normally on display at the San Jacinto Battleground State Historic Site, near Houston, but as of 2021 is closed for repairs.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *North Carolina* is on display in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] *Alabama* is on display in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The USS Arizona Memorial was erected over the wreck of *Arizona*, which was sunk during the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, to commemorate those killed in the raid.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Memorials were also placed to mark the wreck of *Utah*, also sunk during the attack.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The only other 20th-century battleship on display is the Japanese pre-dreadnought *Mikasa*, preserved since 1923.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] On 22 December 2025, the United States Navy announced the planned construction of new battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The Trump class will be the first nuclear-powered battleship, and it is planned to carry nuclear-capable cruise missiles, and conventional weapons.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] For much of their existence, battleships were the embodiment of sea power.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The American naval officer Alfred Thayer Mahan argued in his seminal 1890 work, *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*, a strong navy was vital to the success of a nation, and control of the seas was a prerequisite for the projection of force.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Conversely, countries with weak navies would inevitably decline.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Mahan argued that the cruiser warfare advocated by the *Jeune Ecole* could never be decisive, and that only fleets of battleships could control sea lanes and enforce blockades of an enemy's coast.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The book proved to be widely influential across the world's navies; it was translated into German in 1896, where it was used to support the German naval expansion program championed by Alfred von Tirpitz.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] A Japanese-language translation also appeared in 1896, and it soon became required reading at the Japanese naval academy.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] By the end of the decade, Russian, French, Italian, and Spanish versions were produced.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The "fleet in being" in part acts as a deterrent against attack.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The concept underpinned Tirpitz's so-called "risk theory" that was the basis of his program to build a German battle fleet.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Even if the Royal Navy maintained a numerical superiority, the risk that the German fleet would inflict grievous damage even in the case of a British victory would militate against any such battle taking place, and Germany would be free to pursue its global ambitions.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, naval tacticians had developed a number of formations in which to employ battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The most prominent were referred to as "line ahead" and "line abreast".
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The former, the standard tactic during the age of sail, arrayed ships in a single-file line, which emphasized broadside fire.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The latter placed ships side-by-side, which was suited to close-range melees where ramming and torpedoes could be effectively employed; after Tegetthoff's success at Lissa in 1866 used a modified line abreast formation, the tactic enjoyed a period of popularity for several years.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] By the 1880s, line-ahead tactics had returned to prominence.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Royal Navy officers devised the tactic referred to as "crossing the T" of an enemy fleet, whereby one fleet steaming in line-ahead formation crossed in front of another line of battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] This maneuver would allow one's own battleships to concentrate entire broadsides on the leading enemy ship, while one's opponent could only reply with their forward guns.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Many navies adopted the tactic soon thereafter.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] As the threat of underwater attack, including mines and torpedoes, developed after the 1860s, capital ships could no longer maintain close blockades of enemy ports.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] This required smaller, faster scouts to observe hostile ports so that an enemy fleet could be brought to battle.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Modern cruisers began to be built in the 1880s for this purpose.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Almost immediately after the invention of the airplane, navies recognized its potential as a reconnaissance unit for the fleet's battleships.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The Austro-Hungarian Navy, then following the *Jeune École* doctrine of the 1870s and 1880s, devised the tactic of placing torpedo boats alongside battleships; these would hide behind the larger ships until gun-smoke obscured visibility enough for them to dart out and fire their torpedoes.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] While this tactic was made less effective by the development of smokeless propellant, the threat from more capable torpedo craft (later including submarines) remained.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] By the 1890s, the Royal Navy had developed the first destroyers, which were initially designed to intercept and drive off any attacking torpedo boats.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The other major naval powers quickly followed suit with similar vessels of their own.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The presence of battleships had a great psychological and diplomatic impact.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Similar to possessing nuclear weapons in the second half of the 20th century, the ownership of battleships marked a country as a regional or global power, and the ability to build them domestically signified that a country could claim to be a great power.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Even during the Cold War, the psychological impact of a battleship was significant.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] In September 1983, when Druze militia in Lebanon's Shouf Mountains fired upon U.S.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Marine peacekeepers, the arrival of USS *New Jersey* stopped the firing.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Gunfire from *New Jersey* later killed militia leaders.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] Battleships were the largest and most complex, and hence the most expensive warships of their time; as a result, the value of investment in battleships has always been contested.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] As the French politician Etienne Lamy wrote in 1879, "The construction of battleships is so costly, their effectiveness so uncertain and of such short duration, that the enterprise of creating an armored fleet seems to leave fruitless the perseverance of a people".
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The *Jeune École* school of thought of the 1870s and 1880s sought alternatives to the crippling expense and debatable utility of a conventional battlefleet.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] It proposed what would nowadays be termed a sea denial strategy, based on fast, long-ranged cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo boat flotillas to attack enemy ships attempting to blockade French ports.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The ideas of the *Jeune École* were ahead of their time; it was not until the 20th century that efficient mines, torpedoes, submarines, and aircraft were available that allowed similar ideas to be effectively implemented.
[src:long-ton/battleship-p02] The determination of powers such as Germany to build battlefleets with which to confront much stronger rivals has been criticized by historians, who emphasize the futility of investment in a battlefleet that has no chance of matching its opponent in an actual battle.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The **British thermal unit** (**Btu**) is a measure of heat, which is a form of energy.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] It was originally defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] It is also part of the United States customary units.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The SI unit for energy is the joule (J); one Btu equals about 1,055 J (varying within the range of 1,054–1,060 J depending on the specific definition of Btu; see below).
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] While units of heat are often supplanted by energy units in scientific work, they are still used in some fields.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] For example, in the United States the price of natural gas is quoted in dollars per the amount of natural gas that would give 1 million Btu (1 "MMBtu") of heat energy if burned.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] A Btu was originally defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of liquid water by one degree Fahrenheit at a constant pressure of one atmospheric unit.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] There are several different definitions of the Btu that differ slightly.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] This reflects the fact that the temperature change of a mass of water due to the addition of a specific amount of heat (calculated in energy units, usually joules) depends slightly upon the water's initial temperature.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] As seen in the table below, definitions of the Btu based on different water temperatures vary by up to 0.5%.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Units of kBtu are used in building energy use tracking and heating system sizing.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Energy Use Index (EUI) represents kBtu per square foot of conditioned floor area.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The unit **MBtu** is used in natural gas and other industries to indicate 1,000 Btu.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] However, there is an ambiguity in that the metric system (SI) uses the prefix "M" to indicate 'Mega-', one million (1,000,000).
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Even so, "MMBtu" is often used to indicate one million Btu particularly in the oil and gas industry.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Energy analysts accustomed to the metric "k" ('kilo-') for 1,000 are more likely to use MBtu to represent one million, especially in documents where M represents one million in other energy or cost units, such as MW, MWh and $.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The unit 'therm' is used to represent 100,000 Btu.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] A decatherm is 10 therms or one million Btu.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The unit *quad* is commonly used to represent one quadrillion (1015) Btu.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] A Btu can be approximated as the heat produced by burning a single wooden kitchen match or as the amount of energy it takes to lift a one-pound (0.45 kg) weight 778 feet (237 m).
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The SI unit of power for heating and cooling systems is the watt.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Btu *per hour* (Btu/h) is sometimes used in North America and the United Kingdom—the latter for air conditioning mainly, though "Btu/h" is sometimes abbreviated to just "Btu".
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] *MBH*—thousands of Btu per hour—is also common.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The Btu should not be confused with the Board of Trade Unit (BTU), an obsolete UK synonym for kilowatt hour (1 kW⋅h or 3,412 Btu).
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The Btu is often used to express the conversion-efficiency of heat into electrical energy in power plants.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Figures are quoted in terms of the quantity of heat in Btu required to generate 1 kW⋅h of electrical energy.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] A typical coal-fired power plant works at 10,500 Btu/kWh (3.1 kWh/kWh), an efficiency of 32–33%.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] The centigrade heat unit (CHU) is the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound (0.45 kg) of water by one Celsius degree.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] In 1974, this unit was "still sometimes used" in the United Kingdom as an alternative to Btu.
[src:long-ton/british-thermal-unit] Another legacy unit for energy in the metric system is the calorie, which is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one gram of water by one degree Celsius.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] The **long ton**, also known as the **imperial ton**, **displacement ton**, or **British ton**, is a measurement unit equal to 2,240 pounds (1,016.0 kg).
[src:long-ton/long-ton] It is the name for the unit called the "ton" in the avoirdupois system of weights or Imperial system of measurements.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] It was standardised in the 13th century.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] It is used in the United States for bulk commodities.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] It is not to be confused with the short ton, a unit of weight equal to 2,000 pounds (907.2 kg) used in the United States, and Canada before metrication, also referred to simply as a "ton".
[src:long-ton/long-ton] A long ton is defined as exactly 2,240 pounds.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] The long ton arises from the traditional British measurement system: A long ton is 20 long hundredweight (cwt), each of which is 8 stone (1 stone = 14 pounds).
[src:long-ton/long-ton] To comply with the practices of the European Union, the British Imperial ton was explicitly excluded from use for trade by the United Kingdom's Weights and Measures Act of 1985.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] The measure used since then is the tonne, equal to 1,000 kilograms.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] If still used for measurement, then the word "ton" is taken to refer to an imperial or long ton.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] In the United States, the long ton is commonly used in measuring the displacement of ships and the shipping of baled commodities and bulk goods like iron ore and elemental sulfur.
[src:long-ton/long-ton] The long ton was the unit prescribed for warships by the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922; for example, battleships were limited to a displacement of 35,000 long tons (35,560 t; 39,200 short tons).
[src:long-ton/long-ton] The long ton is traditionally used as the unit of weight in international contracts for many bulk goods and commodities.
